<p class="guide-intro">Your heart rate is one of the most immediate windows into your cardiovascular health. Whether you are checking your resting heart rate in the morning, training in a specific heart rate zone, or monitoring your fitness progress, knowing what numbers are normal — and what they mean — is essential.</p>

<h2>Normal Resting Heart Rate by Age</h2>
<p>Resting heart rate (RHR) is measured after sitting quietly for at least 5 minutes. The <strong>American Heart Association (AHA)</strong> defines a normal adult RHR as <strong>60–100 bpm</strong>. It typically decreases with age in fit individuals due to improved cardiac efficiency:</p>

<table class="data-table">
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Age Group</th><th>Normal RHR Range</th><th>Athlete Range</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>Children (6–15)</td><td>70–100 bpm</td><td>—</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Adults (18–25)</td><td>62–73 bpm</td><td>49–55 bpm</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Adults (26–35)</td><td>62–73 bpm</td><td>49–54 bpm</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Adults (36–45)</td><td>63–75 bpm</td><td>50–56 bpm</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Adults (46–55)</td><td>63–76 bpm</td><td>50–57 bpm</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Adults (56–65)</td><td>62–75 bpm</td><td>51–56 bpm</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Adults (65+)</td><td>60–73 bpm</td><td>50–55 bpm</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>Maximum Heart Rate by Age</h2>
<p>Maximum heart rate (HRmax) declines with age. The <strong>Tanaka formula</strong> — validated in a 2001 meta-analysis of 351 studies — is more accurate than the older "220 − age" formula, especially for adults over 40:</p>

<p style="background:#f0fdf4;border:1.5px solid #86efac;border-radius:10px;padding:14px 18px;font-family:monospace;font-size:15px;margin:16px 0">
  HRmax = 208 − (0.7 × age)
</p>

<table class="data-table">
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Age</th><th>Est. Max HR (Tanaka)</th><th>Est. Max HR (220−age)</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>20</td><td>194 bpm</td><td>200 bpm</td></tr>
    <tr><td>25</td><td>190 bpm</td><td>195 bpm</td></tr>
    <tr><td>30</td><td>187 bpm</td><td>190 bpm</td></tr>
    <tr><td>35</td><td>184 bpm</td><td>185 bpm</td></tr>
    <tr><td>40</td><td>180 bpm</td><td>180 bpm</td></tr>
    <tr><td>45</td><td>177 bpm</td><td>175 bpm</td></tr>
    <tr><td>50</td><td>173 bpm</td><td>170 bpm</td></tr>
    <tr><td>55</td><td>170 bpm</td><td>165 bpm</td></tr>
    <tr><td>60</td><td>166 bpm</td><td>160 bpm</td></tr>
    <tr><td>65</td><td>163 bpm</td><td>155 bpm</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>Target Heart Rate Zones for Exercise</h2>
<p>Training zones are calculated as a percentage of your HRmax. The <strong>5-zone model</strong> used by most exercise physiologists and coaches:</p>

<table class="data-table">
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Zone</th><th>% of HRmax</th><th>Effort</th><th>Primary Benefit</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>Zone 1 — Recovery</td><td>50–60%</td><td>Very easy</td><td>Active recovery, warm-up</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Zone 2 — Fat Burn</td><td>60–70%</td><td>Light / conversational</td><td>Fat oxidation, aerobic base</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Zone 3 — Aerobic</td><td>70–80%</td><td>Moderate</td><td>Cardiovascular endurance</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Zone 4 — Threshold</td><td>80–90%</td><td>Hard</td><td>Lactate threshold, speed</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Zone 5 — Max</td><td>90–100%</td><td>Maximum effort</td><td>Peak power, VO2 max</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>Resting Heart Rate and Cardiovascular Fitness</h2>
<p>Lower resting heart rate is a reliable marker of cardiovascular fitness. A 2018 study in the <em>European Heart Journal</em> (n=800,000) found that a resting HR above 80 bpm was associated with significantly elevated risk of cardiovascular mortality compared to 45–60 bpm. Each 10 bpm increase in resting HR was associated with a 16% increase in all-cause mortality risk in men and 12% in women.</p>
<p>Regular aerobic exercise — particularly sustained Zone 2 training — is the most effective way to lower resting heart rate over time. Even 150 minutes per week of moderate-intensity cardio can reduce RHR by 5–10 bpm within 8–12 weeks.</p>

<h2>When to Be Concerned</h2>
<p>Seek medical evaluation if you experience:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Resting HR consistently above 100 bpm (tachycardia) without obvious cause</li>
  <li>Resting HR consistently below 60 bpm with symptoms of dizziness, fatigue, or fainting (bradycardia in non-athletes)</li>
  <li>Irregular pulse or palpitations — skipped, racing, or fluttering beats</li>
  <li>Heart rate that does not return to near-normal within 5 minutes of stopping moderate exercise</li>
</ul>
<p>A single elevated reading is rarely cause for alarm. Trend matters more than any single measurement — track your resting HR over days or weeks for a meaningful picture.</p>

<h2>How to Measure Your Resting Heart Rate</h2>
<p>For the most accurate reading: measure first thing in the morning before getting out of bed. Place two fingers (index and middle) on your wrist (radial artery) or neck (carotid artery). Count beats for 60 seconds, or count for 30 seconds and multiply by 2. Repeat 3 days in a row and average the results.</p>

